";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:2:{s:4:"name";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4:"Mark";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:3:"uri";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:24:"http://diveintomark.org/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}}}}}s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:25:"Ribbon Hero is the future";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:3:"rel";s:9:"alternate";s:4:"type";s:9:"text/html";s:4:"href";s:54:"http://diveintomark.org/archives/2010/03/03/microgames";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:2:"id";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"tag:diveintomark.org,2010-03-04:/archives/20100304041900";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:7:"updated";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"2010-03-05T02:48:19Z";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:9:"published";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:20:"2010-03-04T04:19:00Z";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"scheme";s:23:"http://diveintomark.org";s:4:"term";s:7:"unfiled";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:2:{s:6:"scheme";s:23:"http://diveintomark.org";s:4:"term";s:6:"gaming";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:7:"summary";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:21:"ACHIEVEMENT UNLOCKED!";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}s:7:"content";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2603:"<p>Several things:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://lostgarden.com/2010/01/ribbon-hero-turns-learning-office-into.html">Ribbon Hero turns learning Office into a game</a>. Sounds like the worst game ever to me, but <a href="http://www.officelabs.com/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=90">it&#8217;s been downloaded 32,000 times</a>, so what do I know?</li>
<li><a href="http://exogen.github.com/nose-achievements/">Unit Testing Achievements</a>. It&#8217;s unclear whether this is a joke. It hits the same blind spot as <a href="http://eis-blog.ucsc.edu/2010/02/space-invaders-enterprise-edition/">Space Invaders Enterprise Edition</a>. It&#8217;s <em>just believable enough</em> that you can&#8217;t rule it out <i>a priori</i>. (Update: apparently neither of these is a joke.)</li>
<li><a href="http://www.krazydad.com/blog/2010/02/mayor-of-the-north-pole/">Mayor of the North Pole</a> chronicles one man&#8217;s journey to hack the <a href="http://foursquare.com/">Foursquare</a> <abbr>API</abbr> and <a href="http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2010/02/confessions-of-a-foursquare-cheater.html">piss off a lot of people</a> who were proud of being the &#8220;mayor&#8221; of their neighborhood Starbucks.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.reddit.com/help/awards">Reddit Awards</a> are designed to encourage specific behavior, like voting on articles in the /new queue or posting great comments. There is <a href="http://www.reddit.com/awards">a daily honor roll of winners</a>.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.gamasutra.com/blogs/GregMcClanahan/20091202/3709/Achievement_Design_101.php">Achievement Design 101</a>, from the guy who creates site-wide achievements on <a href="http://www.kongregate.com/">Kongregate</a>.</li>
</ul>

<p>I was never a big player of video games growing up, but I&#8217;ve recently gotten engrossed in them by way of my children. My older son plays New Super Mario Bros. Wii with me. Having finished all the worlds together, I find myself going back and collecting the &#8220;Star Coins,&#8221; of which there are 3 on each level. Some are cleverly hidden, others are out in the open but difficult to get. Collecting them unlocks in-game hint movies, all of which are more easily playable on Youtube &#8212; <em>even my six-year-old son knows this</em> &#8212; but still, I spend hours collecting them, and he high-fives me whenever I unlock a new movie.</p>

<p>It pains me to think that he might grow up doing the same with his cubicle-mates around some future version of Ribbon Hero and some future version of Office, but I suspect that&#8217;s the direction we&#8217;re headed.</p>";s:7:"attribs";a:2:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:4:"type";s:4:"html";}s:36:"http://www.w3.org/XML/1998/namespace";a:1:{s:4:"base";s:54:"http://diveintomark.org/archives/2010/03/03/microgames";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:54:"http://diveintomark.org/archives/2010/03/03/microgames";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:1;s:8:"xml_lang";s:2:"en";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:9:"








